1
00:00:47,400 --> 00:00:50,633
on a cool October day in 1945 

2
00:00:50,633 --> 00:00:51,666
Dr J Robert Oppenheimer

3
00:00:51,666 --> 00:00:54,400
arrived at the White House in Washington DC

4
00:00:55,333 --> 00:00:57,866
a 30 minute meeting had been scheduled with President

5
00:00:57,866 --> 00:00:59,266
Harry S Truman

6
00:01:00,466 --> 00:01:03,400
a meeting that could shape the course of history

7
00:01:07,400 --> 00:01:08,300
that morning Doctor

8
00:01:08,300 --> 00:01:09,133
Robert Oppenheimer

9
00:01:09,133 --> 00:01:12,066
was making an attempt to reason with the president

10
00:01:15,933 --> 00:01:18,866
he had just LED a team of scientists in developing

11
00:01:18,866 --> 00:01:19,933
and testing a weapon

12
00:01:19,933 --> 00:01:21,600
that helped bring about the end of

13
00:01:21,600 --> 00:01:22,933
the Second World War

14
00:01:26,066 --> 00:01:27,333
now he was desperate

15
00:01:27,333 --> 00:01:29,700
to prevent the world from destroying itself

16
00:01:34,833 --> 00:01:37,933
after the atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki

17
00:01:38,066 --> 00:01:40,400
Oppenheimer had followed military developments

18
00:01:40,400 --> 00:01:41,800
with deep concern

19
00:01:45,800 --> 00:01:48,700
he felt compelled to personally share his fears

20
00:01:48,700 --> 00:01:49,900
about this devastating

21
00:01:49,900 --> 00:01:52,333
new weapon with the American president

22
00:02:00,233 --> 00:02:02,066
the events of October

23
00:02:02,066 --> 00:02:05,033
1945 marked a turning point in history

24
00:02:05,733 --> 00:02:08,033
but the story began years earlier

25
00:02:08,033 --> 00:02:11,300
with Hitler's invasion of Poland in 1939

26
00:02:11,433 --> 00:02:13,533
which triggered the Second World War

27
00:02:16,066 --> 00:02:18,433
as German forces advanced across Europe

28
00:02:18,933 --> 00:02:22,433
European emigre physicists working in the United States

29
00:02:22,533 --> 00:02:24,666
Learned that their counterparts in Berlin

30
00:02:24,666 --> 00:02:26,700
were experimenting with nuclear fission

31
00:02:30,700 --> 00:02:32,866
fearing its potential as a weapon

32
00:02:33,266 --> 00:02:35,100
they approached Albert Einstein

33
00:02:35,233 --> 00:02:37,800
and persuaded him to collaborate in writing a letter

34
00:02:37,800 --> 00:02:40,433
warning President Franklin D Roosevelt

35
00:02:43,633 --> 00:02:45,266
the letter raised the alarm

36
00:02:45,266 --> 00:02:45,833
that Nazi

37
00:02:45,833 --> 00:02:49,066
Germany might be the first to develop an atomic bomb

38
00:02:51,033 --> 00:02:53,733
in response Roosevelt mobilized US

39
00:02:53,733 --> 00:02:55,666
resources to stay ahead

40
00:02:59,033 --> 00:03:00,500
by executive order

41
00:03:00,500 --> 00:03:03,333
he created the Manhattan Engineer District

42
00:03:03,600 --> 00:03:05,000
placing atomic research

43
00:03:05,000 --> 00:03:07,533
at the center of the American war effort

44
00:03:11,300 --> 00:03:13,600
to lead this unprecedented project

45
00:03:13,600 --> 00:03:15,800
the army appointed General Leslie Groves

46
00:03:15,800 --> 00:03:16,866
a seasoned officer

47
00:03:16,866 --> 00:03:19,500
who had recently overseen construction of the Pentagon

48
00:03:19,500 --> 00:03:20,333
in Washington DC

49
00:03:20,333 --> 00:03:23,533
a significant military achievement

50
00:03:29,033 --> 00:03:29,666
undergrows

51
00:03:29,666 --> 00:03:32,600
the Manhattan Engineer District grew rapidly

52
00:03:32,700 --> 00:03:35,466
employing 75,000 Americans

53
00:03:38,266 --> 00:03:40,300
its structure was compartmentalized

54
00:03:40,300 --> 00:03:43,100
to protect secrecy and maintain focus

55
00:03:45,000 --> 00:03:47,600
Groves knew he needed a brilliant scientist

56
00:03:47,900 --> 00:03:49,800
someone who could lead with vision

57
00:03:49,866 --> 00:03:52,100
rally the nation's top minds

58
00:03:52,300 --> 00:03:54,866
and drive progress at a record pace

59
00:03:55,833 --> 00:03:57,533
after careful consideration

60
00:03:57,533 --> 00:04:00,000
General Groves arrived at his decision

61
00:04:03,866 --> 00:04:07,800
I was completely responsible for the selection of Dr

62
00:04:08,133 --> 00:04:09,133
Oppenheimer

63
00:04:09,733 --> 00:04:13,666
as the head of the Los Alamos Bomb Laboratory

64
00:04:15,700 --> 00:04:16,666
Dr. Oppenheimer

65
00:04:16,666 --> 00:04:18,833
already knew many of the top scientists

66
00:04:18,833 --> 00:04:20,233
and physicists of the era

67
00:04:21,300 --> 00:04:22,466
he had the charisma

68
00:04:22,466 --> 00:04:24,333
intellect and leadership skills

69
00:04:24,333 --> 00:04:26,900
needed to unite them behind a single mission

70
00:04:29,900 --> 00:04:32,500
when Groves and Oppenheimer met for the first time

71
00:04:32,733 --> 00:04:35,466
their top priority was finding a remote location

72
00:04:35,466 --> 00:04:37,100
for a secret laboratory

73
00:04:38,333 --> 00:04:40,300
where the scientists could live and work

74
00:04:40,300 --> 00:04:41,400
around the clock

75
00:04:41,400 --> 00:04:43,033
in complete isolation

76
00:04:45,933 --> 00:04:48,900
Oppenheimer suggested a place in northern New Mexico

77
00:04:48,900 --> 00:04:50,900
where he had spent time with his family

78
00:04:52,833 --> 00:04:54,300
he had hiked the hills

79
00:04:54,400 --> 00:04:56,333
ridden horses through the terrain

80
00:04:56,433 --> 00:04:58,500
and even leased a simple cabin there

81
00:05:02,100 --> 00:05:05,233
he remembered a nearby ranch school set on a Mesa

82
00:05:09,100 --> 00:05:10,666
it seemed ideal

83
00:05:11,800 --> 00:05:13,733
the two men drove out to see it

84
00:05:15,433 --> 00:05:17,900
the old school grounds had solid infrastructure

85
00:05:17,900 --> 00:05:20,400
access to water and room for expansion

86
00:05:20,666 --> 00:05:23,700
Groves turned to Oppenheimer and said this is it

87
00:05:24,666 --> 00:05:27,433
the property was quickly secured for the government

88
00:05:27,866 --> 00:05:31,200
and work began immediately on guardhouses and roads

89
00:05:32,433 --> 00:05:35,233
Oppenheimer started assembling a team of top scientists

90
00:05:35,233 --> 00:05:38,000
engineers and experts from across the country

91
00:05:39,266 --> 00:05:42,100
a laboratory was built and structures began to rise

92
00:05:42,100 --> 00:05:43,333
almost overnight

93
00:05:44,333 --> 00:05:47,100
hundreds of workers and support staff arrived

94
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:50,800
the guardhouse soon became a hub of activity

95
00:05:52,333 --> 00:05:54,700
scientists came with their families

96
00:05:54,833 --> 00:05:57,066
among them was Oppenheimer's wife Catherine

97
00:05:57,066 --> 00:05:58,066
known as Kitty

98
00:05:58,233 --> 00:06:01,100
who was his confidant and constant companion

99
00:06:06,900 --> 00:06:09,200
Kitty welcomed new arrivals

100
00:06:09,333 --> 00:06:11,200
organized social events

101
00:06:11,333 --> 00:06:14,633
and became the de facto first lady of Los Alamos

102
00:06:18,100 --> 00:06:19,733
as research advanced

103
00:06:19,900 --> 00:06:20,900
military planners

104
00:06:20,900 --> 00:06:23,200
began searching for a nearby location

105
00:06:23,200 --> 00:06:25,900
to test the world's first atomic bomb

106
00:06:30,033 --> 00:06:33,000
the test site needed to be far from populated areas and

107
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:34,800
inaccessible to the public

108
00:06:35,700 --> 00:06:39,433
a location north of Alamogordo New Mexico was selected

109
00:06:40,933 --> 00:06:44,100
it lay in a desert known as the Jordana del Muertos

110
00:06:44,233 --> 00:06:46,500
Spanish for “journey of the dead”

111
00:06:47,733 --> 00:06:50,300
the area had already been secured by the military

112
00:06:50,300 --> 00:06:52,133
and used for bombing practice

113
00:06:55,733 --> 00:06:57,500
eyewitnesses later recalled that

114
00:06:57,500 --> 00:07:00,466
Oppenheimer played a key role in selecting the site

115
00:07:01,833 --> 00:07:04,800
he reportedly slept under a truck during the search

116
00:07:04,800 --> 00:07:06,633
and seemed more at ease in the desert

117
00:07:06,633 --> 00:07:08,200
than many of his colleagues

118
00:07:11,300 --> 00:07:12,033
over time

119
00:07:12,033 --> 00:07:15,233
a small base camp rose from the barren terrain

120
00:07:15,466 --> 00:07:17,900
Oppenheimer named the site Trinity

121
00:07:20,633 --> 00:07:23,600
several buildings were constructed at the test location

122
00:07:23,600 --> 00:07:25,733
including barracks and a canteen

123
00:07:26,333 --> 00:07:28,800
there was even a pool table for the workers

124
00:07:35,666 --> 00:07:37,900
when the bomb was finally ready for testing

125
00:07:37,900 --> 00:07:40,066
a tall steel tower was built

126
00:07:40,233 --> 00:07:42,333
the idea was to detonate the device above

127
00:07:42,333 --> 00:07:45,266
ground to better observe and measure its effects

128
00:07:47,266 --> 00:07:49,300
by late April 1945

129
00:07:49,300 --> 00:07:51,800
Allied forces had retaken most of Germany

130
00:07:51,800 --> 00:07:53,700
and were closing in on Berlin

131
00:07:59,033 --> 00:08:00,533
Berlin soon fell

132
00:08:00,533 --> 00:08:03,433
and the entire country came under Allied control

133
00:08:04,133 --> 00:08:05,900
German soldiers surrendered

134
00:08:05,933 --> 00:08:08,900
and many members of the Nazi regime were captured

135
00:08:10,700 --> 00:08:11,200
American

136
00:08:11,200 --> 00:08:13,900
intelligence teams recovered a vast trove of secret

137
00:08:13,900 --> 00:08:15,300
military documents

138
00:08:16,066 --> 00:08:17,500
after Germany's surrender

139
00:08:17,500 --> 00:08:21,066
US intelligence agents rushed to the Pina Munda rocket facility

140
00:08:21,266 --> 00:08:22,433
where Werner von Braun

141
00:08:22,433 --> 00:08:25,500
had LED the development of the German V2 rocket

142
00:08:30,733 --> 00:08:32,333
in a nearby cave

143
00:08:32,633 --> 00:08:36,700
American troops discovered 14 tons of technical papers

144
00:08:36,866 --> 00:08:39,033
and hundreds of rocket components

145
00:08:42,266 --> 00:08:45,066
but the agents uncovered an even greater secret

146
00:08:45,700 --> 00:08:48,633
that the Germans under von Proun's supervision

147
00:08:48,700 --> 00:08:51,500
had been developing a rocket intended to strike

148
00:08:51,500 --> 00:08:52,800
New York City

149
00:08:56,333 --> 00:08:59,133
alongside tons of rocket components

150
00:08:59,233 --> 00:09:01,300
technical drawings and documents

151
00:09:01,700 --> 00:09:04,466
the American troops discovered that Dr von brown

152
00:09:04,466 --> 00:09:06,233
and his team of German scientists

153
00:09:06,233 --> 00:09:08,000
were working on the development

154
00:09:08,000 --> 00:09:10,733
of long range weapons that might one day reach

155
00:09:10,733 --> 00:09:12,433
transatlantic targets

156
00:09:14,200 --> 00:09:15,866
this research they realized

157
00:09:15,866 --> 00:09:18,133
could be of great benefit to the US military

158
00:09:18,633 --> 00:09:21,000
the findings were quickly relayed to President Truman

159
00:09:21,000 --> 00:09:22,700
who ordered all materials

160
00:09:22,700 --> 00:09:24,000
and the scientists

161
00:09:24,100 --> 00:09:26,600
to be secured and shipped to the United States

162
00:09:26,600 --> 00:09:27,600
without delay

163
00:09:30,433 --> 00:09:32,400
the US military acted swiftly

164
00:09:32,433 --> 00:09:34,600
transporting the rocket parts and equipment

165
00:09:34,600 --> 00:09:35,466
technical documents

166
00:09:35,466 --> 00:09:38,533
and more than 100 German scientists and their families

167
00:09:38,533 --> 00:09:40,300
including Bernhard von brown

168
00:09:40,333 --> 00:09:41,800
to the United States

169
00:09:44,866 --> 00:09:46,200
the Pentagon decided

170
00:09:46,200 --> 00:09:49,100
the best location for this top secret cargo

171
00:09:49,100 --> 00:09:50,933
was the New Mexico desert

172
00:09:51,100 --> 00:09:52,900
near the atomic test site

173
00:09:54,433 --> 00:09:56,000
almost overnight

174
00:09:56,133 --> 00:09:59,700
New Mexico became the focal point of global attention

175
00:10:01,266 --> 00:10:02,100
it was now home

176
00:10:02,100 --> 00:10:05,100
not only to Los Alamos and the Trinity test site

177
00:10:05,300 --> 00:10:05,800
but also

178
00:10:05,800 --> 00:10:08,900
the centre of a newly planned rocket testing range

179
00:10:14,233 --> 00:10:16,333
although the allies now controlled Germany

180
00:10:16,333 --> 00:10:17,500
and much of Europe

181
00:10:17,500 --> 00:10:19,600
Japan continued to fight fiercely

182
00:10:19,600 --> 00:10:21,000
in the Pacific Theater

183
00:10:27,466 --> 00:10:29,733
in the weeks following Germany's surrender

184
00:10:29,733 --> 00:10:31,900
a conference of Allied leaders was planned

185
00:10:31,900 --> 00:10:34,466
to address Europe's postwar administration

186
00:10:34,866 --> 00:10:35,666
and to coordinate

187
00:10:35,666 --> 00:10:38,533
the final stages of the war against Japan

188
00:10:39,800 --> 00:10:42,133
the meeting was scheduled to begin on July 17

189
00:10:42,133 --> 00:10:44,466
1945 in Potzdam

190
00:10:44,900 --> 00:10:47,866
and later became known as the Potzdam Conference

191
00:10:51,133 --> 00:10:54,000
Truman's secretary of war Henry Stinson

192
00:10:54,433 --> 00:10:57,100
who received daily updates on the Manhattan Project

193
00:10:57,233 --> 00:11:00,833
was aware that the first atomic bomb test was imminent

194
00:11:02,933 --> 00:11:04,400
Stimpson requested

195
00:11:04,400 --> 00:11:05,600
that President Truman

196
00:11:05,600 --> 00:11:08,400
authorise an accelerated timeline for the test

197
00:11:08,400 --> 00:11:10,033
in the desert of New Mexico

198
00:11:10,900 --> 00:11:11,133
so

199
00:11:11,133 --> 00:11:13,600
that its outcome could align with the opening of the

200
00:11:13,600 --> 00:11:15,200
Potsdam Conference

201
00:11:20,266 --> 00:11:22,300
if the test proved successful

202
00:11:22,433 --> 00:11:24,033
Truman could enter the conference

203
00:11:24,033 --> 00:11:25,333
with news of a powerful

204
00:11:25,333 --> 00:11:26,000
new weapon

205
00:11:26,000 --> 00:11:29,033
as leverage for his negotiations with the allies

206
00:11:30,400 --> 00:11:32,700
Truman agreed to the accelerated timeline

207
00:11:32,700 --> 00:11:34,400
and instructed General Groves

208
00:11:34,400 --> 00:11:36,833
to notify the Los Alamos scientists

209
00:11:36,933 --> 00:11:40,233
that the test must occur before the Potsdam meeting

210
00:11:40,400 --> 00:11:42,533
meaning no later than July

211
00:11:44,066 --> 00:11:46,500
Dr Oppenheimer called a meeting at Camp Lodge

212
00:11:46,500 --> 00:11:47,633
in Los Alamos

213
00:11:49,500 --> 00:11:51,200
the scientists agreed that

214
00:11:51,200 --> 00:11:53,900
with full cooperation across all departments

215
00:11:53,900 --> 00:11:56,033
the test could be moved forward

216
00:11:58,133 --> 00:12:01,100
enriched plutonium was prepared in the Los Alamos lab

217
00:12:01,100 --> 00:12:02,300
ahead of the test

218
00:12:04,800 --> 00:12:06,833
under Oppenheimer's supervision

219
00:12:07,133 --> 00:12:10,100
the plutonium was loaded onto military vehicles

220
00:12:13,233 --> 00:12:15,833
it was then driven south through New Mexico

221
00:12:16,200 --> 00:12:19,033
arriving hours later at the Trinity site

222
00:12:19,466 --> 00:12:21,700
340 km away

223
00:12:33,400 --> 00:12:34,466
with great care

224
00:12:34,466 --> 00:12:37,066
the components were assembled at the test site

225
00:12:38,200 --> 00:12:40,900
the plutonium core was inserted into the bomb

226
00:12:40,900 --> 00:12:42,700
nicknamed the gadget

227
00:12:45,300 --> 00:12:47,433
under Oppenheimer's watchful eye

228
00:12:47,433 --> 00:12:49,666
the team completed the final assembly

229
00:12:54,666 --> 00:12:55,933
in the tower above

230
00:12:56,100 --> 00:12:58,933
men were prepared to lift the bomb using hoists

231
00:12:59,266 --> 00:13:00,800
while those below worked the pulleys

232
00:13:00,800 --> 00:13:02,866
the team at the top monitored the process

233
00:13:02,866 --> 00:13:03,933
using mirrors

234
00:13:05,300 --> 00:13:06,866
once the bomb reached the top

235
00:13:06,866 --> 00:13:08,133
the floor was sealed

236
00:13:08,133 --> 00:13:10,433
and technicians wired and inspected the device

237
00:13:10,433 --> 00:13:13,200
to ensure the test could proceed as planned

238
00:13:16,533 --> 00:13:18,666
Oppenheimer notified General Groves

239
00:13:18,666 --> 00:13:20,800
that the test was ready for July 16

240
00:13:23,300 --> 00:13:25,733
Groves relayed the news to President Truman

241
00:13:25,733 --> 00:13:28,266
who was already at the conference in Potsdam

242
00:13:30,100 --> 00:13:31,533
on the morning of the test

243
00:13:31,600 --> 00:13:34,100
light rain and distant lightning threatened a delay

244
00:13:34,600 --> 00:13:36,500
but the skies eventually cleared

245
00:13:37,700 --> 00:13:39,400
at 5 29 a m

246
00:13:39,400 --> 00:13:40,533
on July 1945

247
00:13:40,533 --> 00:13:44,200
the world's first atomic bomb was detonated

248
00:13:44,200 --> 00:13:45,800
in the New Mexico desert

249
00:13:50,066 --> 00:13:52,200
the atomic age had begun

250
00:13:56,133 --> 00:13:58,900
The United States now possessed a weapon capable of

251
00:13:58,900 --> 00:14:01,866
ending the war and compelling Japan to surrender

252
00:14:05,233 --> 00:14:07,900
news of the successful test was sent immediately

253
00:14:07,900 --> 00:14:08,933
to President Truman

254
00:14:08,933 --> 00:14:11,333
in Potsdam via courier telegram

255
00:14:13,200 --> 00:14:14,433
the message read

256
00:14:15,600 --> 00:14:17,200
Doctor has just returned

257
00:14:17,200 --> 00:14:19,400
most enthusiastic and confident

258
00:14:19,400 --> 00:14:22,233
that the little boy is as husky as his big brother

259
00:14:25,333 --> 00:14:26,866
a New York Times reporter

260
00:14:26,866 --> 00:14:28,866
who was part of the official observation group

261
00:14:28,866 --> 00:14:30,400
later described the moment

262
00:14:30,666 --> 00:14:34,200
as if he were present when god created the first light

263
00:14:34,900 --> 00:14:37,600
General Groves recorded in his classified report

264
00:14:37,600 --> 00:14:39,000
that the bomb test was

265
00:14:39,100 --> 00:14:39,600
probably

266
00:14:39,600 --> 00:14:42,266
more important than the discovery of electricity

267
00:14:43,066 --> 00:14:44,100
back at the control room

268
00:14:44,100 --> 00:14:47,033
the scientists reacted with a mix of awe and unease

269
00:14:47,066 --> 00:14:48,133
one of them remarked

270
00:14:48,333 --> 00:14:50,666
we are probably now all sons of bitches

271
00:14:51,433 --> 00:14:53,333
cigarettes and beer were passed around

272
00:14:53,333 --> 00:14:55,000
in subdued Celebration

273
00:14:55,500 --> 00:14:59,633
the explosion had been audible from 160 kilometers away

274
00:15:01,500 --> 00:15:03,266
to avoid public alarm

275
00:15:03,633 --> 00:15:05,333
a press release was issued

276
00:15:05,433 --> 00:15:05,933
claiming that

277
00:15:05,933 --> 00:15:08,800
a munitions depot had accidentally exploded

278
00:15:14,066 --> 00:15:16,500
just hours after the successful test

279
00:15:16,533 --> 00:15:19,666
the USS Indianapolis set sail from San Francisco

280
00:15:19,933 --> 00:15:22,233
heading for the Pacific island of Tinian

281
00:15:23,466 --> 00:15:25,733
on board were components and plutonium

282
00:15:25,733 --> 00:15:27,133
for a second bomb

283
00:15:27,233 --> 00:15:29,200
intended for use against Japan

284
00:15:34,533 --> 00:15:37,333
meanwhile with news of the test in hand

285
00:15:37,333 --> 00:15:38,200
President Truman

286
00:15:38,200 --> 00:15:40,266
showed a noticeable shift in confidence

287
00:15:40,266 --> 00:15:41,100
